<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  installer/macos-pkg/scripts/lib/vz.entitlements

  D-18 P-021. Apple Virtualization.framework entitlement plist applied
  to every Lima/Colima Mach-O that creates or hosts a VZ virtual
  machine: limactl, the Lima 2.x external lima-driver-vz driver, and
  the lima binary itself.

  Without com.apple.security.virtualization, "colima start" with
  vm-type vz on Apple Silicon fails inside Lima's VZ driver with:

      Error Domain=VZErrorDomain Code=2
      "Invalid virtual machine configuration. The process doesn't have
       the com.apple.security.virtualization entitlement."

  Observed live on the customer Mac mini (postinstall round 4,
  2026-05-05) against MiningGuardian-1.0.3-47efd658f16a.pkg: colima
  start succeeded through Lima version handshake, downloaded plus
  converted the disk image, then the VZ driver subprocess hit the
  entitlement check and exited 1.

  Mirrors the upstream lima-vm/lima vz.entitlements (top-level file in
  that repo, applied via codesign with the entitlements flag in lima's
  Makefile to both _output/bin/limactl and
  _output/libexec/lima/lima-driver-vz). Our build_pkg.sh
  (step_4b_codesign_inner_binaries) re-signs every vendored Mach-O
  with Developer ID Application + hardened runtime + secure timestamp
  for Apple notarization; that re-sign drops the upstream ad-hoc
  entitlements unless we explicitly re-pass them via the entitlements
  flag. The fix is to pass this file on the codesign call for every
  VZ-needing binary.

  Network entitlements are included to match upstream lima. Lima's VZ
  driver creates the VM's vmnet attachment from inside its own
  process, and bridged-network-device attachment requires both
  com.apple.security.network.server and com.apple.security.network.client.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.network.server</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.virtualization</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
